Chapter 1
Cohren
04:30 Itanian time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He especially hated it because he was responsible for waking up all the others in his company. Silently, he got off his bunk, put on his combat suit, threw on his protective vest, and retrieved his belongings from the locker, being careful around a particular small box. He shouldered his rifle and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Attached to it were everything he needed, such as his breathing apparatus or his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, the mud and ice crunched under his boots.
He pulled a lighter out of one jacket pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short puff before opening the door slightly. In the last week, he had come up with various ways to wake the men and women under his command. He no longer used the preset alarm clock, as it usually didn't work and only produced faint static from the speakers.
“Wake them up?” Cohren turned around and saw Zugführer Nemic approaching him.
„Ja,“ antwortete Cohren.
„Womit wollen Sie es dieses Mal versuchen?“
Bevor er antworten konnte, öffnete sich die Tür und Harris, Craith und ein paar andere kamen ihm bereits in voller Montur entgegen.
„Guten Morgen,“ sagte Craith.
„Wovon sind Sie denn wach geworden?“, fragte Cohren.
„Firstly, we weren’t in the mood to wait for whatever you have in store for us today. And secondly, the assault troops who get up first should be able to choose their morning ration,“ one of the men, Ravik, replied. „And you know how terrible the food can be.“
„Good point, Sergeant,“ said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. In the barracks, a sharp, loud alarm sounded. Inside, he heard muffled curses and people running around.
„Come on, Valteri,“ said Nemic. „One would think they’ve learned by now to wake up at the same time as you.“
„Well, my guys from the training camp have,“ Cohren replied and pointed at Harris, Craith, and Ravik. „However, the squad and platoon leaders also know they have to rise before their units.“
A few seconds later, the rest of the company came out. They had everything they needed, from personal items to necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others appeared irritated.
„Good morning,“ said Cohren cheerfully.
„With all due respect, sir, why do you have to wake us up like this?“ asked a Stormtrooper Sergeant.
„Because the regular alarms stink and because Daybreak doesn't oversleep,“ said Cohren.
„Pack all your personal items,“ Cohren continued. As the deputy captain and executing officer of the company, he was responsible for overseeing and supporting the company together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. „We won't be coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your teams have 15 minutes for the final checks and to pack your rations.“
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second Stormtrooper Division, second army. Before they were combined, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren had mixed feelings about his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Zugführer Nemic walked side by side under the light of many generator-powered lamps of the forward base. Most had red-tinted glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild-Weasel attacks from the air and ground to counter them.
„A new day and a new task for the Hellhounds,“ said Nemic with a dry laugh. „Where are they sending us?“
„A forward base outside Ianlos. We will support the ground attack,“ answered Cohren and took a drag on his cigarette. He owed some of the blame for starting to smoke to Craith, but a year in service changed a man, so he said nothing.
„Shit. Things are getting worse at the front,“ muttered Nemic. „All reports read: «Support war efforts. Send help to the Kurgan front.» What about the Howland front?“
„Amen, brother,“ said Cohren and flicked the ashes of his cigarette into the mud. „At least we start with the first armed platoon and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be there.“
„Did Shaw arrange a ride for us?“ Nemic asked a bit surprised.
„Yes. He's actually not as bad as I thought. Not very friendly, but you can manage with him.“
Cohren held his thumb and index finger to his throat microphone and adjusted his backpack. „All units of the Exodus Company meet at the West vehicle park when you're ready. We'll depart with the first armed platoon at 0500.“
Second by second, he received responses from the platoon leaders. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking sergeants when they all arrived here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt as if he had known them forever, though it was only two years. They were platoon leaders, but Craith had taken over the second platoon for the past week, as the previous leader had been medically discharged after being shot by a Daybreak sniper.
On the way to the vehicle park, Cohren and Nemic noticed a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four armored personnel carriers. The crews were walking around, ensuring their machines were ready for action. Quickly, Cohren spotted Captain Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armed platoon. As they approached, Shaw looked over at them with his expressionless face and came toward them.
„Lieutenant Nemic… Lieutenant Valteri…“ He said, Cohren is slower, while looking at Cohren's pistol holster and then looking up. „I assume the company is ready?“
